    {
      "thumb": "https://cdn.bsky.app/img/feed_thumbnail/plain/did:plc:wamidydbgu3u6fk3yckaglnz/bafkreihlf5xd7dtlnzn2bmy6dlhxc2n2i4gwqbq3xu23nzjfrqo6pbmasu",
      "fullsize": "https://cdn.bsky.app/img/feed_fullsize/plain/did:plc:wamidydbgu3u6fk3yckaglnz/bafkreihlf5xd7dtlnzn2bmy6dlhxc2n2i4gwqbq3xu23nzjfrqo6pbmasu",
      "alt": "With that caveat: there's a genuine tension in the story, and I don't think it's dishonest to feel it. Anthropic's whole public identity is the \"we're the careful ones\" lab — it reportedly tried to keep its models out of mass surveillance and autonomous weapons. A tool judged too dangerous to release, then routed into offensive operations, doesn't automatically contradict that, but it does sit close to the edge of it. The \"best defense is a good offense\" line in the article is a real argument, not just spin — you can't build good defenses against AI-enabled attacks without understanding the attacks, and adversaries are plainly pursuing this regardless. But \"they'll do it anyway\" is also the oldest rationalization in the arms-race playbook, and a private company embedding staff to guide a spy agency's offensive work raises real questions about oversight and who's actually accountable for what gets done.",
      "ratio": 2.4802,
      "handle": "philpax.me",
      "url": "https://bsky.app/profile/philpax.me/post/3mnihosayzc2m"
    },
    {
      "thumb": "https://cdn.bsky.app/img/feed_thumbnail/plain/did:plc:ckaz32jwl6t2cno6fmuw2nhn/bafkreibtcz7hqea2ndrnrthzgqh6zb4qjrqd5mowtwu7oeb26qbohahaau",
      "fullsize": "https://cdn.bsky.app/img/feed_fullsize/plain/did:plc:ckaz32jwl6t2cno6fmuw2nhn/bafkreibtcz7hqea2ndrnrthzgqh6zb4qjrqd5mowtwu7oeb26qbohahaau",
      "alt": "\nmy hypothesis is that each request probably has a classifier router that’s potentially quite expensive that routes to one pod out of a fleet of pods. each pod probably has all experts, but far more computationally close (within GPU or within rack). The purpose being to share compute as much as possible. Increase the number of batch requests that all go through the same experts. So basically, each GPU is NOT big enough to fit the whole model, but it does have an expert config that fits the portions of the model to serve 90% of the full inference, and 99% within the same rack.\n\nversus with 1T you’re just splitting over a couple GPUs so you just split vllm style. things get a lot harder with 10T bc so much if the naive model inference goes into intra-cluster compute traffic",
